Time Limit: 1 sec
Memory: 256 MB

Description
Given a number N and an array A of N numbers. Print the numbers after sorting them.

Note:
Don't use built-in functions.

Try to solve it with Bubble Sort algorithm or Selection Sort.

For more information, watch: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q-NXg6Tzyks](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q-NXg6Tzyks)

Input Format
The first line contains T, the number of test cases.

For each test case:
The first line contains N, the number of elements.
The second line contains N space-separated integers denoting the array.

Output Format
For each test case, print the numbers after sorting them.

Constraints
1 ≤ T ≤ 10
1 ≤ N ≤ 10³
−100 ≤ Aᵢ ≤ 100

Sample Input 1
1
3
3 1 2

Sample Output 1
1 2 3

Sample Input 2
2
3
3 1 2
4
5 2 7 3

Sample Output 2
1 2 3
2 3 5 7

Note

For Sample Input 1:
We have one test case with N = 3.
The array is [3, 1, 2].
After sorting, the array becomes [1, 2, 3].

For Sample Input 2:
We have two test cases.

Test case 1:
N = 3, array = [3, 1, 2]
After sorting, array = [1, 2, 3]

Test case 2:
N = 4, array = [5, 2, 7, 3]
After sorting, array = [2, 3, 5, 7]



#include<iostream>
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--)
    {
        int n;
    cin>>n;
    vector<int>v(n);
    for(int i = 0 ; i< n; i++)
    {
        cin>>v[i];
    }

    sort(v.begin(),v.end());

    for(int i = 0 ; i< n; i++)
    {
      cout<<v[i]<<" ";
    } 
    
    cout<<endl;
    }
    
}
